WEBVTT

00:06.000 --> 00:12.074
Advertise your product or brand here
contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

00:37.214 --> 00:42.093
<i>I am a headhunter and I am
the purest form of salesman alive.</i>

00:42.135 --> 00:44.304
<i>I sell the American dream.</i>

00:44.346 --> 00:47.850
<i>I make money out of thin air,
smoke, whole cloth.</i>

00:47.892 --> 00:50.228
<i>I stand on the shoulders of giants,</i>

00:50.269 --> 00:52.396
<i>the hardest of hardened salesmen.</i>

00:52.438 --> 00:56.359
<i>Tin men, bible salesmen, slum realtors.</i>

00:56.400 --> 00:59.612
<i>We're a wolf pack of commissioned
phone jockeys working</i>

00:59.654 --> 01:03.074
<i>70 hours a week without a net.
You hit, you hit big.</i>

01:03.115 --> 01:05.534
<i>You blank, and the repo man's tailgating</i>

01:05.576 --> 01:07.411
<i>the minivan at the grocery store.</i>

01:07.453 --> 01:11.666
<i>This job is a desk, a phone,
a chair and your ass.</i>

01:13.250 --> 01:15.836
Good morning,
Imperial Automotive Manufacturing,

01:15.878 --> 01:17.172
Dottie speaking.

01:17.214 --> 01:19.216
<i>I am who I say I am.</i>

01:19.257 --> 01:20.217
Johnny Cobra calling, Dot.

01:20.217 --> 01:22.177
Need the name of your
Plant Manager, please.

01:22.219 --> 01:24.846
<i>I'm sorry, but it's
against company policy</i>

01:24.888 --> 01:27.641
to give out names of employees.
Nature of your business, sir?

01:27.683 --> 01:29.601
The nature of
my business, Dottie, is that

01:29.643 --> 01:31.186
I'm down here at the Nissan plant with

01:31.186 --> 01:33.898
a shut-down line costing me
ninety grand a minute

01:33.940 --> 01:36.734
because your Quality Department
thinks they can run a freightliner

01:36.776 --> 01:39.946
full of injection molded crap
down my goddamn throat!

01:39.988 --> 01:43.074
The person that you need to
speak to is Mr. Rayburn, I'll...

01:43.116 --> 01:45.118
First name, first name, first name.

01:45.159 --> 01:46.744
Thomas is his first name.

01:46.786 --> 01:48.455
Dottie./ What?

01:48.497 --> 01:50.665
Relax. Take a deep breath.
Pat yourself on the back,

01:50.707 --> 01:53.209
you're doing one helluva job./
<i>Well, thank you,</i>

01:53.251 --> 01:56.337
uh, Mr... did you say "Cobra"?

01:57.380 --> 01:58.506
Call me Johnny.

01:58.548 --> 02:01.676
Dot, tell me, what's the story on Tom?
Big guy, small guy,

02:01.718 --> 02:05.180
young, old, play sports, college boy,
what am I dealing with?

02:05.222 --> 02:07.516
I know Tommy does play golf a lot.

02:07.558 --> 02:10.185
He's been working here
a couple three years, probably...

02:10.227 --> 02:13.105
Oh, chitchat's over, Dot.
Boss is on my ass.

02:13.105 --> 02:14.523
Go on patch me through.

02:16.191 --> 02:18.819
Rayburn./ <i>Tom.</i>

02:18.861 --> 02:21.823
Dane Jensen, Blackridge Recruiting.
Thanks for taking my call.

02:21.865 --> 02:24.200
Yeah, hold up, hold up, bud.
Lemme save us both some time.

02:24.200 --> 02:26.745
I'm not lookin' to make
a move right just yet.

02:26.786 --> 02:29.122
Rough as things are out there,
I'm just happy to have the job

02:29.122 --> 02:31.458
I got.
Now I'm up to my ass in alligators

02:31.499 --> 02:34.294
so if you'll excuse me.../
Sweet. Baby. Jesus.

02:34.335 --> 02:37.339
I cannot believe my guy
was wrong about you.

02:37.381 --> 02:41.176
Scuse me? Your guy? What guy?/
This isn't a random call, Tom.

02:41.217 --> 02:43.636
I was told by a confidential source

02:43.678 --> 02:47.348
that even if your golf game was more
screwed up than a soup sandwich,

02:47.390 --> 02:50.268
you're one of the premier
Plant Managers in the South.

02:50.310 --> 02:53.439
He also told me even though
you've only been at Imperial

02:53.481 --> 02:55.316
for three years,
that you were bright enough

02:55.357 --> 02:57.193
to at least listen to
what I was recruiting for

02:57.193 --> 03:01.030
before making up your mind.

03:02.448 --> 03:06.452
So. You're a headhunter, huh?

03:06.494 --> 03:10.207
<i>I am a headhunter.
And a headhunter cometh.</i>

03:10.248 --> 03:13.418
What's the deal with this gut, son?

03:13.460 --> 03:16.588
You need to get some exercise,
buddy, you're starting to look like

03:16.630 --> 03:18.465
the kind of kid Willy Wonka'd kick out

03:18.507 --> 03:19.925
of the chocolate factory.

03:19.966 --> 03:21.468
Hands up.

03:21.510 --> 03:23.596
I dunno, we could play a little football

03:23.638 --> 03:25.973
when you get home tonight./
If it's still light out

03:26.015 --> 03:29.434
and I don't have
any calls to make, we'll see.

03:37.525 --> 03:40.238
Good morning./ <i>Hey, hon.</i>

03:40.279 --> 03:41.948
Ryan eat breakfast?

03:41.989 --> 03:44.951
If you can call it that./
He likes cereal and it's easy.

03:44.992 --> 03:48.371
Of course he does, Elise,
what kid doesn't like

03:48.412 --> 03:50.122
colored marshmallows
swimming in whole milk?

03:50.122 --> 03:52.208
It's a Momma.

03:55.379 --> 03:58.257
I like your hair, Lauren,

03:58.298 --> 04:00.842
looks good on you.

04:00.884 --> 04:03.929
The point is, he's a mess./
Shh! Be quiet, he'll hear you!

04:03.971 --> 04:06.640
Anyway, I made an appointment
for him to see the doctor.

04:06.682 --> 04:08.600
What the hell for, his weight?

04:08.642 --> 04:12.438
No! I told you a week ago, he's tired
all the time and those bruises...

04:12.480 --> 04:15.232
Bruises?/
Mom, can I have chocolate milk?

04:15.232 --> 04:18.777
Sure you can, baby./ Yeah, just a sec.

04:22.113 --> 04:24.908
Who's calling you so early?/
Just some candidate.

04:24.908 --> 04:27.537
Pushing sixty and wonders
why he can't find a job.

04:27.578 --> 04:30.623
Because of his age?
That's awful.

04:30.665 --> 04:31.582
Okay.

04:34.002 --> 04:35.294
Gotta go.

04:35.336 --> 04:37.338
I was thinking maybe
I could drive into the city,

04:37.380 --> 04:38.756
we could get lunch.

04:38.756 --> 04:43.595
First of the month, hon, swamped.
Call me! Oh.

04:51.103 --> 04:55.024
I'm done talking about it!
Either manage Bob to get a deal

04:55.274 --> 04:57.485
or make the son of a bitch
quit so I don't have to pay

04:57.527 --> 04:59.487
unemployment on his lazy ass.

04:59.529 --> 05:01.781
Ed, how do you propose
I force the man to quit?

05:01.823 --> 05:03.283
For Christ sake, Wilson,

05:03.324 --> 05:06.577
have a little fun for a change.

05:06.618 --> 05:09.747
You know what I love about this place?

05:09.788 --> 05:11.123
I'm on pins and needles.

05:11.165 --> 05:14.252
Ed only cares about making money.

05:14.294 --> 05:16.504
Man, woman, black, white, old or young,

05:16.546 --> 05:20.175
doesn't matter as long as
you're a producer.

05:20.216 --> 05:22.385
Bob, were you not here
this past Saturday or Sunday?

05:22.427 --> 05:25.346
No, I don't think anyone was here.

05:25.388 --> 05:28.601
You blanked for three months./
I got two kids,

05:28.642 --> 05:30.060
my wife had divorced me,

05:30.102 --> 05:31.812
I started coming in on the weekends.

05:31.854 --> 05:35.024
Ah, wife and two kids, I see.
You're gonna score in October?

05:35.065 --> 05:37.318
I'm sure gonna try my best.

05:37.359 --> 05:40.988
Try? Your attitude is to try?
Bob...

05:41.030 --> 05:42.406
You know what I hate about this place?

05:42.406 --> 05:43.616
Nope.

05:43.657 --> 05:46.328
Ed only cares about making money.

05:46.369 --> 05:47.788
That's why he tolerates you
and your mouthbreathers.

05:47.788 --> 05:50.582
My mouthbreathers make more placements

05:50.624 --> 05:53.626
and out-produce those Ivy Leaguers
you coddle every month.

05:53.667 --> 05:56.962
What about an attitude that says
"I'll do whatever it takes,

05:57.004 --> 05:59.381
"I'll work whatever hours necessary,

05:59.423 --> 06:04.804
in order to justify your
financial commitment to me, Ed"?

06:07.265 --> 06:10.018
Oh...

06:10.060 --> 06:13.605
Bob...

06:13.647 --> 06:17.235
Are you going to get a deal?!

06:17.276 --> 06:20.446
Yes! Yes, sir.

06:20.488 --> 06:24.242
Attaboy, Bob. Now get
the fuck back on the phone.

06:32.376 --> 06:35.712
Bet the place is full this weekend.

06:35.754 --> 06:39.967
But... if and when Bob leaves,

06:40.008 --> 06:41.926
then keep your ears open.

06:41.968 --> 06:43.928
If he breaches his non-compete

06:43.970 --> 06:46.305
and calls just one of our clients,

06:46.347 --> 06:48.058
I will sue him so deep and hard,

06:48.100 --> 06:50.269
that he, his wide-assed
Junior League wife,

06:50.310 --> 06:53.313
and their two brats will be
sleeping in a cardboard box

06:53.355 --> 06:55.774
under the overpass on Whacker.

06:55.816 --> 06:59.111
There's always someone
that thinks they can hang up

06:59.152 --> 07:01.947
their own shingle, and skip on
down to the home office

07:01.989 --> 07:05.118
in their skivvies and make
phone calls while the rug rats frolic

07:05.159 --> 07:08.454
at their feet. It makes me
want to puke blood.

07:08.496 --> 07:10.748
In 35 years,

07:10.790 --> 07:13.668
I have never let anyone
slide on their non-compete.

07:18.298 --> 07:20.759
I leave for Prague in two days.

07:20.801 --> 07:22.219
Prague?

07:22.261 --> 07:24.847
You want her to tell you where it is?

07:24.888 --> 07:29.392
I know where Prague is.
Overseas.

07:29.434 --> 07:33.104
I want to spend more time
away from the place, travel,

07:33.146 --> 07:36.900
indulge my inner Kerouac.

07:36.942 --> 07:39.695
Time to finalize that succession
plan that we dance around

07:39.737 --> 07:41.155
and never do anything about.

07:41.196 --> 07:43.991
I won't give up control immediately,

07:44.033 --> 07:46.493
but one of you will get the job.

07:46.535 --> 07:50.874
Whoever takes this last quarter
can move into the empty office

07:50.915 --> 07:53.626
next to this one.
You'll get off a desk

07:53.668 --> 07:55.003
and you'll receive overrides

07:55.045 --> 07:57.130
from every recruiter at Blackridge.

07:57.172 --> 08:01.342
I'll announce the new General Manager
the first of the year. Understood?

08:01.384 --> 08:03.803
One hundred percent, Ed./ Understood.

08:03.845 --> 08:07.850
Wilson, beat it.

08:24.283 --> 08:26.786
The hell is that?/ Cobra wine.

08:26.827 --> 08:31.040
Spotted it in a small village in Vietnam
last month, thought of you.

08:31.081 --> 08:33.333
You're supposed to drink it?/
Don't be such an American.

08:33.333 --> 08:34.919
Of course you drink it.

08:34.960 --> 08:38.298
But I'm determined to save it
for a special occasion.

08:38.340 --> 08:41.134
Maybe the next time I do
something truly remarkable.

08:41.176 --> 08:42.510
Such as?

08:42.552 --> 08:44.846
I haven't settled on that as yet.

08:44.888 --> 08:47.599
How about a record-breaking October?

08:47.641 --> 08:49.559
What makes a person remarkable
is the life they live,

08:49.559 --> 08:50.977
not the money they make.

08:51.019 --> 08:52.938
Spoken like a man with a lot of money.

08:54.857 --> 08:57.693
I may never uncork that wine.

08:58.736 --> 09:00.363
Ryan...

09:00.404 --> 09:02.907
Ryan, wake up, pal.

09:02.949 --> 09:06.326
What time is it?/ 6:30. Come on.

09:06.368 --> 09:09.205
Let's get some roadwork in
before school.

09:09.247 --> 09:10.748
Roadwork?

09:15.586 --> 09:18.464
Dad! I need to rest.

09:18.506 --> 09:21.175
Why don't I just carry you?

09:21.217 --> 09:24.846
I'm walking./ You're jogging.

09:24.888 --> 09:26.890
Morning, ladies!

09:31.645 --> 09:33.188
Alright.

09:33.230 --> 09:36.066
Let's just walk.

09:36.108 --> 09:38.944
Why don't we go to Catholic school?

09:40.863 --> 09:43.783
We're lapsed Catholics.

09:43.825 --> 09:45.159
The good Lord wants us to spend

09:45.201 --> 09:47.203
Sunday mornings at Cracker Barrel.

09:47.245 --> 09:49.622
I'm with the Lord.

09:51.541 --> 09:53.501
How come Lauren doesn't have to jog?

09:53.543 --> 09:55.962
'Cause Lauren doesn't have
to lose weight.

09:57.880 --> 10:00.508
First step in solving a problem
is recognizing it, buddy.

10:00.550 --> 10:03.011
Did you and Grandpa go jogging
when you were a kid

10:03.052 --> 10:06.389
in St. Louis?/ No, not hardly.

10:06.431 --> 10:07.849
He went to work when it was dark,

10:07.890 --> 10:09.017
came home when it was dark.

10:09.017 --> 10:11.311
Wasn't much fun, was he?

10:11.352 --> 10:14.023
Eh, he did the job.

10:15.774 --> 10:18.444
"Kinfe," "Sizhong," "Deepak",

10:18.485 --> 10:21.155
don't get me going on the red dots.

10:21.196 --> 10:22.740
Here's an invoice begging to be sent.

10:22.740 --> 10:26.035
"Ping."
Interview a Chinese engineer yet?

10:26.076 --> 10:28.538
Treat yourself. It's like having
a conversation in the dark

10:28.580 --> 10:30.415
with Astro from the Jetsons.

10:30.457 --> 10:33.168
Look, Sumner,

10:33.209 --> 10:34.711
I should have spent
more time with you, okay.

10:34.711 --> 10:36.046
My fault. Let's start over.

10:36.087 --> 10:39.090
We are the "Dixie Mafia."
Okay, Dixie.

10:39.132 --> 10:41.384
The South. You know,
state's rights, NASCAR,

10:41.426 --> 10:43.595
closeted atheists, poor spellers.

10:43.636 --> 10:45.013
I'm not an idiot, Mr. Jensen.

10:45.055 --> 10:47.891
Okay. Role-play with me, alright.

10:47.932 --> 10:50.018
I'm a client from
Hattiesburg, Mississippi and

10:50.060 --> 10:51.603
I'm looking for a process engineer.

10:51.644 --> 10:55.690
So go on, pitch me one of your PhD's.

10:55.732 --> 10:58.610
Ahem! Ring! Ring!

10:58.651 --> 11:01.947
Darrel Waltrip here!/
Uh, yes, Mr. Waltrip?

11:01.989 --> 11:04.617
Darrel, son.
What can I do you for?

11:04.658 --> 11:06.160
Well, Darrel, I'm calling about your...

11:06.160 --> 11:08.662
Who the hell is this?

11:08.704 --> 11:09.997
Sumner, Sumner Firestone
from Blackridge Recruiting.

11:09.997 --> 11:11.290
Spit it out, I'm a busy man!

11:11.332 --> 11:14.795
Uh... well, I've got a guy, he's uh,

11:14.836 --> 11:17.172
for your open engineering
position I mean,

11:17.214 --> 11:19.549
he's got two degrees in
Mechanical Engineering,

11:19.591 --> 11:21.134
experience reducing waste in the plants.

11:21.134 --> 11:22.803
Sounds stronger than puppy's breath.

11:22.844 --> 11:23.804
Now, when can he get down here?

11:23.804 --> 11:27.849
Well, he can be there Friday?/
You asking me or telling me?

11:27.891 --> 11:29.518
I'm telling you.
He'll be there Friday.

11:29.559 --> 11:32.104
Friday it is! By the by,

11:32.145 --> 11:35.065
he wouldn't happen to have
one of those PhD's, would he?

11:35.107 --> 11:36.525
As a matter of fact, he does.

11:36.566 --> 11:39.277
Perfect!
Better'n a new set of snow tires!

11:39.319 --> 11:41.947
Now, what's his name?

11:41.988 --> 11:45.242
Mohammed Al Far...

11:45.283 --> 11:48.412
Your sleeper-cell starter kits

11:48.454 --> 11:52.708
are unemployable south of the grit-line!

11:57.713 --> 12:01.425
Alright. Cowboy up, sunshine.

12:01.467 --> 12:04.471
Use this guy. Lou Wheeler.

12:04.555 --> 12:07.641
Bachelor's in Mechanical Engineering,
Six Sigma experience,

12:07.683 --> 12:09.476
and an age-vague voice.

12:09.518 --> 12:12.229
"Age-vague"?/ Yeah. He's 59,

12:12.271 --> 12:14.857
sounds like he's 39, and
refuses to change the dates

12:14.898 --> 12:16.650
on his resume, and is unemployable.

12:16.692 --> 12:18.653
Why unemployable?

12:18.695 --> 12:22.906
He's 59 and refuses to lie about it.
God, you and my wife.

12:22.948 --> 12:25.701
Okay... so why do I want him?

12:25.742 --> 12:28.453
Because we will

12:28.495 --> 12:31.123
take 15 years off Lou's resume.

12:31.164 --> 12:32.499
Right, but once he goes
in for the interview,

12:32.499 --> 12:33.585
they'll just see how old he is, I mean,

12:33.585 --> 12:35.461
what's the point?

12:35.503 --> 12:36.754
We don't send him on an interview.

12:36.754 --> 12:39.549
Lou's what you call a Tracer Bullet.

12:39.591 --> 12:42.051
A tracer bullet, you know?

12:42.093 --> 12:43.177
A round that lights up

12:43.219 --> 12:45.054
so you know where to fire
the rest of the real bullets.

12:45.054 --> 12:47.348
I know what a tracer bullet is,
I just don't understand...

12:47.348 --> 12:48.891
..."Relatively Young Lou"

12:48.933 --> 12:50.686
is a sure-fire bet for
a phone interview, okay?

12:50.686 --> 12:53.439
But once he's off the line
with a paying customer,

12:53.480 --> 12:56.191
you bleed "Actually Old Lou"
for information.

12:56.233 --> 12:58.152
Like, "What projects
are they working on?"

12:58.193 --> 13:00.404
"What specifically did they ask you?"

13:00.446 --> 13:01.864
And you give that information

13:01.905 --> 13:03.616
to your placeable candidates
to prepare them.

13:03.616 --> 13:06.244
I don't know...

13:06.286 --> 13:08.996
We're headhunters, Sumner.

13:09.038 --> 13:11.832
In an economic shit storm.

13:11.874 --> 13:13.417
Now I can teach you how to count cards,

13:13.417 --> 13:14.668
but I can't make you do it.

13:14.710 --> 13:16.503
So you either reach deep inside

13:16.545 --> 13:18.839
and find that small
dark part of yourself

13:18.881 --> 13:21.801
that's predatory...
Or there's the door.

13:26.306 --> 13:28.391
Alright.

13:28.433 --> 13:31.853
Try giving yourself a desk name,
something tough, visual.

13:31.895 --> 13:34.939
Watch Wall Street,
Godfathers 1 and 2, not 3.

13:34.981 --> 13:37.360
Go on, get your phone, listen in.

13:41.197 --> 13:44.658
Bernadine?

13:44.700 --> 13:47.244
Hey, it's Dane.

13:47.286 --> 13:50.414
How are you, dear?
Is Lou around?

13:52.459 --> 13:54.669
Lou!

13:54.711 --> 13:58.756
Honey, Dane is on the phone!

14:03.344 --> 14:05.304
Hi, Dane!

14:05.346 --> 14:08.558
So, you hear anything from Superior?

14:08.600 --> 14:11.228
Are we gonna get that face-to-face?

14:11.269 --> 14:12.979
<i>Uh, I'm afraid not, Lou.</i>

14:13.021 --> 14:15.482
<i>They tell me they went
with the other guy.</i>

14:15.524 --> 14:17.818
<i>Now I told them they were
making a big mistake, but...</i>

14:17.859 --> 14:21.655
I'm sorry, Lou, I didn't get it done.

14:21.696 --> 14:24.784
Don't blame yourself,
we'll get 'em next time.

14:24.826 --> 14:27.662
Lou, I'm bringing in
another person to help.

14:27.703 --> 14:30.790
His name's Sumner Firestone,
he's a great guy.

14:30.832 --> 14:33.459
Recruiting savant.

14:33.501 --> 14:35.545
We have any other prospects
on the horizon that look good?

14:35.545 --> 14:37.672
No, not at the moment, Lou.

14:37.713 --> 14:39.258
But we are all over this.

14:39.299 --> 14:40.801
You call me when you
hear something, okay?

14:40.801 --> 14:44.471
<i>Will do.</i>

14:56.775 --> 14:59.778
So, how did it go?/ Oh, they uh,

14:59.820 --> 15:03.657
they decided to go with
the other candidate, no big deal.

15:03.699 --> 15:07.703
Thank heavens!/ What?

15:07.744 --> 15:11.291
I'm sorry, sweetie,
I know you were interested

15:11.332 --> 15:13.835
in doing this job, but...

15:13.877 --> 15:17.088
I was praying that
we wouldn't have to go to Mobile.

15:17.130 --> 15:20.258
I have no desire to see
a hurricane up close.

15:20.300 --> 15:22.510
Besides,

15:22.552 --> 15:25.263
after 29 years,

15:25.305 --> 15:29.685
I kinda like having you home with me.

15:29.727 --> 15:33.146
Bea, it's been nearly a year.

15:33.187 --> 15:36.107
And?

15:36.149 --> 15:39.027
Are you complaining?

15:46.744 --> 15:50.164
Three layoffs in eight months.
Your plant is dying.

15:50.205 --> 15:52.833
I can hear the death rattle from here.
And when it does,

15:52.875 --> 15:56.503
the only steady job you're gonna
find within a hundred miles

15:56.545 --> 15:59.174
of Elkhart won't require
an engineering degree,

15:59.215 --> 16:02.260
but a little blue vest and the phrase
"Hi, welcome to Walmart."

16:02.302 --> 16:04.512
What am I missing?

16:04.554 --> 16:06.014
