59:47.785 --> 59:51.164
would consider "marketable."

59:55.084 --> 59:58.795
But I know how to prioritize.

01:00:20.819 --> 01:00:23.030
You okay over there?

01:00:23.072 --> 01:00:24.865
No.

01:00:59.859 --> 01:01:04.155
Holy crap./ Words right outta my mouth.

01:01:24.720 --> 01:01:29.474
What do we know?/
The designer is Frank Gehry.

01:01:29.516 --> 01:01:32.477
The guy also did a museum in Spain,

01:01:32.519 --> 01:01:36.022
and he probably did
some other stuff too...

01:01:36.063 --> 01:01:40.026
But I do remember a quote of his.

01:01:40.068 --> 01:01:44.197
"When everybody else
is ready for the ending,

01:01:44.239 --> 01:01:46.533
I'm just ready to begin."

01:01:46.575 --> 01:01:50.662
I like Frank.

01:01:50.704 --> 01:01:54.709
Me too, buddy.

01:01:54.751 --> 01:01:57.420
Hey, Dad?

01:01:57.462 --> 01:02:00.131
Yeah?

01:02:00.173 --> 01:02:04.260
Do you believe in God?

01:02:08.265 --> 01:02:11.435
Depends on the month I'm having.

01:02:11.477 --> 01:02:14.313
Me too.

01:02:20.694 --> 01:02:23.947
Did you have a girlfriend
when you were as old as me?

01:02:25.866 --> 01:02:29.787
Why do you ask?

01:02:29.828 --> 01:02:34.333
Cause there's this girl
in my class. Her name

01:02:34.374 --> 01:02:36.627
is Shawna.

01:02:36.668 --> 01:02:40.673
I think she likes me.

01:02:42.884 --> 01:02:45.178
Shawna, huh?

01:02:45.220 --> 01:02:47.931
Sounds exotic.

01:02:52.352 --> 01:02:55.814
<i>He'll get worse before he gets better...</i>

01:02:55.856 --> 01:02:57.107
<i>Worse?! How can he...</i>

01:02:57.149 --> 01:02:58.984
<i>Ryan's cancer is unusually aggressive.</i>

01:02:59.026 --> 01:03:00.194
<i>Virus!/ HIV.</i>

01:03:00.236 --> 01:03:02.905
<i>He's telling us our boy's going to die.</i>

01:03:02.947 --> 01:03:04.949
<i>Don't you get it? Jesus, Dane,
what are we going to do?</i>

01:03:04.949 --> 01:03:06.784
<i>Cancer is not a negotiation, Mr. Jensen.</i>

01:03:10.079 --> 01:03:12.873
No, twenty people lose
their job, it's a layoff.

01:03:12.915 --> 01:03:14.625
Just you, it's a termination.

01:03:14.667 --> 01:03:16.627
I told you that before the interview.

01:03:16.669 --> 01:03:18.212
The top end is 70.

01:03:18.254 --> 01:03:20.714
Forty years old,
a wife and three kids...

01:03:20.756 --> 01:03:22.341
how do you not pass a drug test?

01:03:22.383 --> 01:03:24.635
When I started recruiting
on this, you told me

01:03:24.677 --> 01:03:26.136
there were five must-haves for this job.

01:03:26.136 --> 01:03:29.557
Your guy has one.
Maybe. I can't justify the fee.

01:03:30.517 --> 01:03:32.936
It's about three now,

01:03:32.978 --> 01:03:35.188
so I expect he'll be back
from his meeting...

01:03:35.230 --> 01:03:37.482
I don't know, maybe five?/
Would you ask Lou

01:03:37.524 --> 01:03:39.776
to call me when he's...

01:03:39.818 --> 01:03:42.571
Uh, what kind of meeting is it?

01:03:42.613 --> 01:03:46.033
He got a call from another
head... from another recruiter.

01:03:46.075 --> 01:03:48.953
It was just last night./ Bernadine?

01:03:48.995 --> 01:03:50.079
Hello?

01:03:50.121 --> 01:03:52.123
Bernadine, hey./ Dane.

01:03:52.164 --> 01:03:56.043
Bernadine? Hello?/ Sumner tells me

01:03:56.085 --> 01:03:57.712
Lou has an interview?
That's wonderful!

01:03:57.753 --> 01:04:00.006
You're not upset?

01:04:00.047 --> 01:04:01.924
Upset? I'll be the first one
to congratulate him,

01:04:01.924 --> 01:04:03.426
no matter how he finds a job.

01:04:03.467 --> 01:04:06.304
You're joking, right?
Listen up, monkeys,

01:04:06.345 --> 01:04:09.932
I need fresh meat to peddle, stat!
Process Engineer.

01:04:09.974 --> 01:04:13.060
Oh, he is very excited, Dane.

01:04:13.102 --> 01:04:15.897
It's an Engineering Manager spot.

01:04:15.939 --> 01:04:19.985
That's fantastic! Scratch that!
Engineering Manager!

01:04:20.027 --> 01:04:22.904
The drive's a little long, but doable.

01:04:22.946 --> 01:04:25.907
Gimme a drive-in, 423 area code!

01:04:25.949 --> 01:04:29.327
But Dane, it means
we wouldn't have to sell.

01:04:29.369 --> 01:04:32.707
I mean, we're just... we're just hoping.

01:04:32.749 --> 01:04:36.627
So am I. You're both
in my family's prayers.

01:04:36.669 --> 01:04:39.464
Bernadine...

01:04:39.505 --> 01:04:42.717
What company is he interviewing with?

01:04:42.759 --> 01:04:44.802
Now, I'm not a pushy man
by nature, Paul,

01:04:44.844 --> 01:04:47.597
ordinarily I don't get this excited

01:04:47.638 --> 01:04:49.307
about a candidate.
But when I told my guy

01:04:49.348 --> 01:04:51.225
that I was going to call you, he went...

01:04:51.267 --> 01:04:54.771
pardon my vulgarity...
ape shit./ I don't know.

01:04:54.812 --> 01:04:58.232
Degreed engineer, really
mature for such a young man...

01:04:58.274 --> 01:05:01.195
no wife, no kids, easy relo.

01:05:01.236 --> 01:05:04.615
But the best thing is, he knows exactly

01:05:04.656 --> 01:05:06.450
what you guys are trying to do
over there...

01:05:06.450 --> 01:05:08.327
and he wants to be a part of it.

01:05:08.368 --> 01:05:11.330
Now what time tomorrow morning
do you want him to be there?

01:05:11.371 --> 01:05:13.207
I think we might have found
the seasoning...

01:05:13.248 --> 01:05:14.291
we've been looking for.

01:05:14.333 --> 01:05:16.293
Seasoning's good.

01:05:16.335 --> 01:05:20.089
But some clichs are clichs for
a reason. Particularly the one

01:05:20.131 --> 01:05:22.759
about old dogs, new tricks.

01:05:25.011 --> 01:05:27.639
Eight AM sharp, Mr. Cobra.

01:05:42.737 --> 01:05:45.740
Dr. Singh?

01:05:50.371 --> 01:05:54.583
How are you, my friend?/ Tired.

01:05:54.625 --> 01:05:57.127
The T cells we treated

01:05:57.169 --> 01:06:00.089
are fighting the cancer in you.

01:06:02.007 --> 01:06:06.346
Dr. Singh? Your hat...

01:06:06.388 --> 01:06:09.391
Why do you wear it?

01:06:11.518 --> 01:06:14.813
I am a Sikh.

01:06:14.854 --> 01:06:18.400
My turban represents my constant
devotion to my religion.

01:06:20.528 --> 01:06:23.030
What do Sikhs believe?

01:06:25.740 --> 01:06:28.493
It's my experience

01:06:28.535 --> 01:06:32.289
that all religions are
some version of your, uh,

01:06:32.330 --> 01:06:34.791
'what goes around comes around.'

01:06:42.967 --> 01:06:46.387
We believe in the dignity
of everyone regardless

01:06:46.429 --> 01:06:50.725
of race, age, man, woman.

01:06:50.766 --> 01:06:53.687
A devout Sikh would protect

01:06:53.729 --> 01:06:56.690
with his own life the poor and the weak.

01:06:58.608 --> 01:07:01.862
Ryan...

01:07:01.903 --> 01:07:05.365
If I could take your sickness

01:07:05.407 --> 01:07:09.954
on myself and away from you,

01:07:09.996 --> 01:07:12.372
I would.

01:07:25.762 --> 01:07:27.722
Hey, buddy.

01:07:27.764 --> 01:07:30.183
Hey, Dad.

01:07:30.224 --> 01:07:32.894
Are you missing your party?

01:07:35.063 --> 01:07:38.107
Hey, honey, how you feeling?

01:07:38.149 --> 01:07:40.736
I'd like to go somewhere.

01:07:58.630 --> 01:08:02.716
There you go, Rhino,
the Wrigley Building.

01:08:02.758 --> 01:08:06.136
Man, that's a lotta Juicy Fruit.

01:08:06.178 --> 01:08:08.514
What do we know, Dad?

01:08:08.555 --> 01:08:11.976
Let's see what we got.

01:08:14.062 --> 01:08:16.981
It was modeled after
the Seville Cathedral's...

01:08:17.023 --> 01:08:19.109
Giralda Tower in Spain.

01:08:19.149 --> 01:08:22.403
Built in 1921.

01:08:22.444 --> 01:08:27.535
It has 250,000 terracotta tiles on it...

01:08:27.576 --> 01:08:30.955
that's why it's so white.

01:08:30.996 --> 01:08:36.210
That and the 116,000-watt
bulbs pointing at it.

01:08:36.252 --> 01:08:39.755
That clock? The hour hand

01:08:39.796 --> 01:08:43.760
is just over six feet long,
the minute hand nine feet.

01:08:43.801 --> 01:08:47.596
How do you know all that?

01:08:47.639 --> 01:08:51.600
There's a bank on the fourth floor.

01:08:51.642 --> 01:08:54.270
I was a teller there
for a little over a year...

01:08:54.310 --> 01:08:55.604
when I was seventeen.

01:08:55.645 --> 01:08:59.359
You worked in there?/ Mm-hmm.

01:08:59.401 --> 01:09:03.029
Awesome.

01:09:03.071 --> 01:09:05.573
Did I know that?

01:09:09.578 --> 01:09:13.124
It was like going to work in a castle.

01:09:13.165 --> 01:09:16.961
Only seventeen.

01:09:17.002 --> 01:09:21.799
And in such a hurry to be older.

01:09:21.841 --> 01:09:24.885
Get on with my life.

01:09:30.892 --> 01:09:33.812
I'm glad we came.

01:09:49.703 --> 01:09:52.331
 I can see your eyes 

01:09:52.372 --> 01:09:56.960
 Underneath these bright city lights 

01:09:57.002 --> 01:10:03.176
 Everything's all right
for a change... 

01:10:03.801 --> 01:10:06.596
Last call at the bar, ladies
and gentlemen. Last call.

01:10:17.191 --> 01:10:21.111
You clean up good./ It's the dress.

01:10:21.153 --> 01:10:25.032
Oh yeah, I see it now./ Asshole.

01:10:26.366 --> 01:10:28.117
How's Ryan?

01:10:31.204 --> 01:10:34.666
How long did Ed last?/ About an hour.

01:10:34.708 --> 01:10:36.710
Stretched it out, did he?

01:10:39.129 --> 01:10:42.424
You did an amazing job.
Situation reversed,

01:10:42.466 --> 01:10:45.844
sick child, I don't know.../
Doing an amazing job.

01:10:45.886 --> 01:10:49.682
Doing.

01:10:51.601 --> 01:10:54.270
You're solid, Wilson.

01:10:54.312 --> 01:10:58.858
You don't cut corners,
you do it the right way.

01:10:58.900 --> 01:11:01.653
Wow.

01:11:01.694 --> 01:11:05.407
You know, for all your macho BS,

01:11:05.449 --> 01:11:07.243
you're the first person
there every morning

01:11:07.284 --> 01:11:09.078
and the last one to go home.

01:11:09.120 --> 01:11:10.913
You're on the phone
from the minute you get in,

01:11:10.913 --> 01:11:13.124
to the minute you leave.

01:11:13.165 --> 01:11:14.416
You're the biggest producer
at the company

01:11:14.416 --> 01:11:15.875
because you're the hardest worker,

01:11:15.917 --> 01:11:18.169
not 'cause any of that
Dixie Mafia nonsense.

01:11:21.882 --> 01:11:25.427
We're not that different, you and I.

01:11:27.346 --> 01:11:30.057
You're so full of shit./
We're very different.

01:11:30.099 --> 01:11:33.060
We're totally different./ Yeah.

01:11:33.102 --> 01:11:36.148
Anyway,

01:11:36.189 --> 01:11:41.111
the month's not over.
I may have a few tricks left.

01:11:43.029 --> 01:11:45.657
No. You don't.

01:11:45.699 --> 01:11:49.661
You're down $20,000 with
ten live interviews on the board.

01:11:49.703 --> 01:11:51.539
Five are wet because
your people are scared of you.

01:11:51.539 --> 01:11:53.332
They're phantoms. I checked.

01:11:53.374 --> 01:11:56.878
That leaves five remaining shots.
Of those, one pays a fee

01:11:56.919 --> 01:11:58.880
that would blow me out of
the water but it's a first interview

01:11:58.880 --> 01:12:00.423
for a VP level position,

01:12:00.464 --> 01:12:02.550
which means it's rolling into next year.
Four shots left.

01:12:02.550 --> 01:12:05.093
Of those, three are interviewing
for the same job.

01:12:05.135 --> 01:12:07.722
Triple coverage, place one,
that's 15,000.

01:12:07.763 --> 01:12:09.140
Which leaves you
with one live interview,

01:12:09.140 --> 01:12:11.142
which, by the way, looks great.

01:12:11.183 --> 01:12:13.811
But the offer is contingent
upon a drug test.

01:12:13.853 --> 01:12:17.106
A drug test he can't pass.
How do I know?

01:12:17.148 --> 01:12:19.734
I heard him tell your guy
about his coke habit

01:12:19.775 --> 01:12:21.068
when I tapped into the call.

01:12:21.110 --> 01:12:24.615
You did what?

01:12:24.656 --> 01:12:27.951
You thought I was going
to rely on the honor system

01:12:27.993 --> 01:12:30.245
with a man who named himself
after a venomous snake

01:12:30.287 --> 01:12:32.873
and keeps a drawer
full of burner phones?

01:12:39.297 --> 01:12:42.800
Merry Christmas, Wilson.

01:12:42.842 --> 01:12:45.428
Go fuck yourself.

01:13:01.444 --> 01:13:05.323
Oh, Ryan, Daddy's here.

01:13:06.699 --> 01:13:09.787
Hey, Rhino.

01:13:09.828 --> 01:13:11.789
Hey...

01:13:11.830 --> 01:13:15.084
You're gonna be all right.

01:13:15.125 --> 01:13:17.878
I promise you.

01:13:17.920 --> 01:13:20.214
You hear me?

01:13:20.255 --> 01:13:24.844
I... I got the Frank Lloyd Wright books.

01:13:24.886 --> 01:13:27.722
And we're gonna go and see
the Thomas Gale House,

01:13:27.764 --> 01:13:30.892
you and me.

01:13:44.280 --> 01:13:46.366
Hi.

01:15:00.402 --> 01:15:02.863
Ryan Jensen's room number, please.

01:15:02.905 --> 01:15:03.989
Are you family, sir?

01:15:04.031 --> 01:15:06.867
Absolutely.

01:15:10.871 --> 01:15:13.081
The ventilator will breathe
for Ryan until such time

01:15:13.123 --> 01:15:15.084
as you decide to stop it.

01:15:15.126 --> 01:15:17.836
Or until he breathes for himself, right?

01:15:17.878 --> 01:15:20.130
Until such time as
he breathes for himself?

01:15:20.172 --> 01:15:23.133
We need to discuss your wishes

01:15:23.175 --> 01:15:25.510
when Ryan codes again.

01:15:25.552 --> 01:15:29.848
When his heart stops./ Correct.

01:15:29.890 --> 01:15:33.227
What's to discuss?
It stops, you start it.

01:15:33.269 --> 01:15:36.940
Ryan is in a coma. He's tired.

01:15:36.981 --> 01:15:40.151
Okay, we got it, thanks.

01:15:54.083 --> 01:15:57.461
Mr. and Mrs. Jensen.
Few things

01:15:57.503 --> 01:16:00.964
are as comforting
for a child as the sound

01:16:01.006 --> 01:16:05.177
of a mother and father's voice.
Perhaps...

01:16:05.219 --> 01:16:08.889
Perhaps you can give Ryan
the chance to heal,

01:16:08.931 --> 01:16:13.060
let the treatment fight the leukemia...

01:16:13.102 --> 01:16:15.896
Please.

01:16:24.447 --> 01:16:28.159
Are you kidding me?
"Sound of a voice"?

01:16:28.201 --> 01:16:30.578
Stop it./ Surrounded by millions

01:16:30.620 --> 01:16:33.415
of dollars' worth
of technology and he says

01:16:33.456 --> 01:16:36.252
"sound of a voice"!/ I said, stop it!

01:16:39.422 --> 01:16:43.008
He's right.

01:16:43.050 --> 01:16:46.137
Kids need their parents, Dane.

01:16:46.178 --> 01:16:48.472
Not just when they're sick.

01:16:51.560 --> 01:16:55.729
Oh, I love Ryan every bit
as much as you do, Elise.

01:16:55.771 --> 01:16:59.150
I know you do.

01:16:59.191 --> 01:17:01.152
I just wish it didn't take him dying

01:17:01.193 --> 01:17:02.486
in order to get your attention.

01:17:02.528 --> 01:17:06.408
That's not fair.

01:17:06.450 --> 01:17:10.203
No, it's not fair.

01:17:10.245 --> 01:17:13.915
But my little boy is dying,

01:17:13.957 --> 01:17:17.878
so I'm not terribly concerned
about what's fair.

01:17:20.882 --> 01:17:23.176
I love you, Dane, but I'll be damned

01:17:23.217 --> 01:17:24.886
if I'm gonna let you keep him hooked up

01:17:24.927 --> 01:17:28.097
to some machine in order
to make up for lost time.

01:18:14.938 --> 01:18:18.066
I'm sorry about Ryan.

01:18:20.860 --> 01:18:23.948
I was with him when
he got his lumbar puncture.

01:18:23.989 --> 01:18:27.284
You know, his spinal tap?

01:18:35.208 --> 01:18:38.795
Anyway, I'm studying for my RN,

01:18:38.836 --> 01:18:43.300
so I try to expose myself
to as many procedures as I can.

01:18:43.342 --> 01:18:47.471
Plus, it helps the kids, right?
When they see a familiar face.

01:18:47.513 --> 01:18:50.349
I keep their mind off
the needle with questions...

01:18:50.391 --> 01:18:53.978
What's Dad do at work,

01:18:54.019 --> 01:18:57.774
what grade they're in,
sport they like to play,

01:18:57.816 --> 01:19:00.235
favorite food,

01:19:00.276 --> 01:19:02.821
just, you know...

01:19:02.862 --> 01:19:04.823
Stuff.

01:19:04.864 --> 01:19:07.575
I'm gonna ask you
another question, Ryan.

01:19:07.617 --> 01:19:10.203
What's your favorite place
in the world, buddy?

01:19:10.245 --> 01:19:12.331
Hmm? Come on, you're doing fine, Ryan.

01:19:12.373 --> 01:19:14.166
What's your favorite place?

01:19:14.208 --> 01:19:16.669
My house./ Your house?

01:19:16.711 --> 01:19:20.088
<i>There's a place on our step
which lets me know</i>

01:19:20.130 --> 01:19:22.173
<i>when Dad's coming up.</i>

01:19:23.967 --> 01:19:26.762
<i>He's the only one big enough
to make the noise.</i>

01:19:26.804 --> 01:19:29.682
<i>He works late a lot.</i>

01:19:29.724 --> 01:19:34.478
<i>But if I leave my light on,
he'll always come in.</i>

01:19:34.520 --> 01:19:37.440
<i>I tell him it's because I like to draw,</i>

01:19:37.481 --> 01:19:40.025
<i>but I really just want to see him.</i>

01:19:40.067 --> 01:19:42.863
<i>When he leaves,</i>

01:19:42.904 --> 01:19:45.866
<i>I can still smell
his cologne for a while.</i>

01:19:45.907 --> 01:19:48.952
<i>It smells like Dad.</i>

01:19:48.994 --> 01:19:51.329
<i>It makes me feel...</i>

01:19:51.371 --> 01:19:53.749
<i>Safe.</i>

01:19:53.790 --> 01:19:57.627
Anyway, I just thought
you'd want to hear it.

01:19:59.630 --> 01:20:03.468
I think I would if my kid
someday thinks I'm a good dad.

01:20:03.509 --> 01:20:05.762
Like yours must.

01:20:11.266 --> 01:20:14.937
Antoine.

01:20:14.979 --> 01:20:18.941
My kid ever say what I did?

01:20:18.983 --> 01:20:21.903
For a living?

01:20:23.988 --> 01:20:26.741
Help other dads get jobs

01:20:26.782 --> 01:20:30.120
so they can take care of their families.

01:21:23.550 --> 01:21:26.553
The Thomas Gale House
is important, not only

01:21:26.595 --> 01:21:29.223
because it showcases the earlier
work of Frank Lloyd Wright,

01:21:29.265 --> 01:21:32.519
but it also hints at his
architectural potential.

01:21:32.560 --> 01:21:34.813
Now, Wright designed the home

01:21:34.854 --> 01:21:37.023
just before he left
the firm Adler and Sullivan.

01:21:37.065 --> 01:21:39.693
He didn't leave.

01:21:39.734 --> 01:21:43.238
Sullivan fired him.

01:21:43.280 --> 01:21:44.446
Because of this house.

01:21:44.488 --> 01:21:46.282
Excuse me, sir, can I help you?

01:21:46.323 --> 01:21:49.744
It's a "bootleg."

01:21:49.786 --> 01:21:53.873
Frank designed it
off the books for the Gale Family.

01:21:53.915 --> 01:21:57.127
See, before, Frank was all

01:21:57.168 --> 01:22:00.714
Prairie Style hard lines

01:22:00.755 --> 01:22:03.967
and cold concrete.

01:22:04.010 --> 01:22:07.096
He designed spaces
that let the light in.

01:22:07.138 --> 01:22:10.766
Rooms that opened up,
then wrapped around you.

01:22:10.808 --> 01:22:16.480
Made a family feel protected, safe.

01:22:16.522 --> 01:22:20.694
Like you belonged here
and only here. Home.

01:22:20.736 --> 01:22:24.197
But Frank was also a gambler,
a risk taker, and he knew

01:22:24.239 --> 01:22:26.199
that if he designed this
off the books for the Gale family,

01:22:26.199 --> 01:22:28.744
his boss might find out.

01:22:30.662 --> 01:22:33.748
Yeah, he knew what
goes around comes around.

01:22:35.667 --> 01:22:38.837
But he also knew that
he could create something

01:22:38.879 --> 01:22:41.757
that would live forever.

01:22:41.798 --> 01:22:44.384
Something magical.

01:22:47.888 --> 01:22:51.851
The magic that stirs men's blood.

01:23:03.613 --> 01:23:06.699
Wheeler residence./ Lou, Dane.

01:23:08.619 --> 01:23:11.914
About time you got off your ass
and went back to work, isn't it?

01:23:11.955 --> 01:23:14.124
Christmas is over, buddy.

01:23:14.166 --> 01:23:16.794
We got a week to get you a job
this year. Chop, chop.

01:23:16.835 --> 01:23:18.504
Think of him as a forty-year-old, Jimmy,

01:23:18.545 --> 01:23:21.130
we'll throw in the other
nineteen years free of charge!

01:23:21.172 --> 01:23:22.966
Hold that thought, Jimmy.

01:23:23.008 --> 01:23:26.678
Dane Jensen.
Hey, Toni, thanks for calling back,

01:23:26.720 --> 01:23:29.723
appreciate it.
Yes, Lou Wheeler.

01:23:29.765 --> 01:23:33.185
No, no, no! Don't you get it?
Every other company in the South

01:23:33.227 --> 01:23:35.854
is thinking first of the year!
You see him now,

01:23:35.896 --> 01:23:39.067
you take him off the market
before they get a crack at him!

01:23:39.108 --> 01:23:40.985
Now, what time Wednesday
works best for you?

01:23:41.027 --> 01:23:42.153
Morning or afternoon?

01:23:42.195 --> 01:23:45.782
Lou? Lou, calm down.

01:23:45.823 --> 01:23:48.743
Tell me, what are you saying
when they ask you,

01:23:48.785 --> 01:23:51.454
"Tell me a little bit about yourself?"

01:23:51.496 --> 01:23:53.665
No, Lou.

01:23:53.706 --> 01:23:57.378
Lou, no, Lou, Lou, stop!

01:23:57.419 --> 01:24:01.298
Christ, brother,
this isn't the biography channel.

01:24:01.340 --> 01:24:04.134
Even I wouldn't hire you.

01:24:04.176 --> 01:24:06.929
Alright.

01:24:06.971 --> 01:24:09.181
Okay. Say this.

01:24:11.100 --> 01:24:14.144
Miss Smith... Toni?

01:24:14.186 --> 01:24:18.774
You know, I've been working
a long time, you can see that.

01:24:18.816 --> 01:24:22.695
And all those years, I've seen
a lot of people come and go.

01:24:24.613 --> 01:24:28.743
I've seen people chasing what
they think will make them happy,

01:24:28.785 --> 01:24:32.580
money, titles, whatever.

01:24:32.622 --> 01:24:35.083
But it seems to me,

01:24:35.125 --> 01:24:37.377
if a man, or a woman,

01:24:37.419 --> 01:24:41.507
can be paid an honest wage
for an honest job,

01:24:41.549 --> 01:24:44.802
and if you can look back
at what you've done

01:24:44.844 --> 01:24:48.514
and feel proud,

01:24:48.556 --> 01:24:52.059
well then, you're happy.

01:24:53.978 --> 01:24:57.023
I know I'm running the risk of
sounding a little old fashioned,

01:24:57.064 --> 01:25:00.109
or naive even, but...

01:25:00.151 --> 01:25:03.946
I don't think you can
ever be too qualified

01:25:03.988 --> 01:25:07.366
to be happy. Do you?

01:25:07.408 --> 01:25:13.665
No, Lou, I don't.

01:25:13.707 --> 01:25:18.045
So. Tell me a little bit about yourself.

01:25:29.015 --> 01:25:32.643
Dane Jensen./ Dane, Toni. You know,

01:25:32.685 --> 01:25:34.520
I've never seen a tighter race
between two candidates.

01:25:34.520 --> 01:25:36.355
We'd like to make an offer.

01:25:39.067 --> 01:25:41.027
He'll take it.

01:25:41.069 --> 01:25:44.155
Whoa, pardner...
Shouldn't I tell you what it is first?

01:25:44.197 --> 01:25:47.742
Yeah, all right.

01:25:47.784 --> 01:25:50.870
Okay, what, what, what are you thinking?

01:25:50.912 --> 01:25:52.497
Well, we're kicking up the pay grade.

01:25:52.538 --> 01:25:54.957
One hundred grand base
salary, full relo,

01:25:54.999 --> 01:25:57.960
no sign-on bonus. Insurance
to start first day of employment.

01:25:58.002 --> 01:26:00.464
Now, it is New Year's Eve and
I plan to start drinking early.

01:26:00.464 --> 01:26:02.341
My math says your fee's 25,000.

01:26:02.382 --> 01:26:04.134
I need that expense
on this year's budget,

01:26:04.176 --> 01:26:07.262
so what do you say we wrap
this up right now. Is he in or out?

01:26:10.432 --> 01:26:14.102
On behalf of Mr. Wheeler, I accept.

01:26:14.144 --> 01:26:16.439
Mr. Wheeler?
No, no, Dane, look,

01:26:16.481 --> 01:26:19.108
we all loved Lou, but he came in second.

01:26:19.150 --> 01:26:20.401
I'm talking about your other guy.

01:26:20.401 --> 01:26:22.278
Other guy? What other guy?

01:26:22.320 --> 01:26:26.157
Ping. As in pong. You know,
the engineer with the doctorate.

01:26:26.199 --> 01:26:27.867
Ping?

01:26:27.909 --> 01:26:29.953
Ten minutes after I schedule
Lou for an interview,

01:26:29.994 --> 01:26:32.456
we get this resume from your
colleague at Blackridge.

01:26:32.498 --> 01:26:35.917
You don't forget a name
like "Race Bannon".

01:26:35.959 --> 01:26:39.087
Just, uh...

01:26:39.128 --> 01:26:43.007
Hang on one sec, Toni.

01:26:43.049 --> 01:26:45.009
Bannon?

01:26:45.051 --> 01:26:47.680
What?

01:26:51.100 --> 01:26:53.227
It doesn't really matter to me
which candidate you hire.

01:26:53.227 --> 01:26:55.020
Good 'cause we're hiring Ping.

01:26:55.062 --> 01:26:58.691
Bannon's my guy, so his deal's my deal.

01:26:58.732 --> 01:27:01.277
I win either way.

01:27:01.318 --> 01:27:03.446
I win.

01:27:03.488 --> 01:27:06.616
What else you got for Lou?

01:27:06.658 --> 01:27:08.743
Position wise? Nothing.

01:27:08.785 --> 01:27:12.330
Plain Jane Engineer, entry level,
temp to hire, anything?

01:27:12.372 --> 01:27:14.416
No, no, and no.

01:27:14.457 --> 01:27:18.044
Look, email me an invoice, Dane,
I gotta run. Happy New Year!

01:27:18.086 --> 01:27:19.839
Wait, who was the better candidate?

01:27:19.880 --> 01:27:21.340
What?

01:27:21.382 --> 01:27:23.883
Who was the best candidate?

01:27:25.802 --> 01:27:28.888
Are you recording this?

01:27:31.891 --> 01:27:35.605
Okay. Fact is,
Lou's the better candidate.

01:27:35.646 --> 01:27:38.107
Now, I can't ask him his age,
but come on...

01:27:38.149 --> 01:27:40.610
<i>How many years does he have
before he calls it a day?</i>

01:27:40.651 --> 01:27:42.278
<i>He's just...</i>

01:27:42.320 --> 01:27:46.240
He's not a good investment.
Between realtor fees,

01:27:46.282 --> 01:27:49.577
closing costs, storage,
relo's gonna run us $40,000,

01:27:49.618 --> 01:27:52.205
temporary living another ten,
and then there's your fee?

01:27:54.499 --> 01:27:57.419
Hire Lou,

01:27:57.461 --> 01:27:59.546
and he's on the house.

01:28:01.465 --> 01:28:03.550
I didn't hear you right.
Say that again?

01:28:03.592 --> 01:28:05.927
You heard right.

01:28:05.970 --> 01:28:09.974
Hire Bannon's guy you pay 25 grand.
Hire Lou? No charge.

01:28:10.016 --> 01:28:12.142
What?

01:28:12.184 --> 01:28:16.772
Why in the world would you
wanna give away 25,000.

01:28:16.813 --> 01:28:19.941
Because he's a good man.

01:28:19.983 --> 01:28:23.821
He has experience no degree can match.

01:28:23.863 --> 01:28:27.200
He's made all the mistakes a guy
half his age hasn't made yet,

01:28:27.241 --> 01:28:30.953
but will, and he's learned
from them all.

01:28:30.995 --> 01:28:35.249
Because he won't lie or pretend
to be something he's not.

01:28:40.464 --> 01:28:44.468
Because everything I need,
I already have.

01:28:44.510 --> 01:28:48.430
And because the price is right, Toni.

01:28:48.472 --> 01:28:53.102
It's a one-time offer,
expires in ten seconds.

01:28:53.143 --> 01:28:55.355
In or out?

01:28:58.316 --> 01:29:01.401
Who was that?

01:29:03.320 --> 01:29:05.405
Lou, what's wrong?

01:29:10.078 --> 01:29:12.622
What would you think
about seeing the grandkids?

01:29:14.541 --> 01:29:16.918
I thought we were gonna wait
until money wasn't so tight.

01:29:16.960 --> 01:29:19.712
I don't mean visiting them,
I mean seeing them.

01:29:19.754 --> 01:29:21.798
Every day, if you want to.

01:29:21.840 --> 01:29:25.010
That was Miss Smith from LOK.

01:29:25.052 --> 01:29:27.555
They're based out in Gainesville.

01:29:27.596 --> 01:29:32.059
That's about, what?
Half an hour away from the kids?

01:29:32.101 --> 01:29:34.812
I'm their new Engineering Manager.

01:29:36.856 --> 01:29:39.233
Gosh!

01:29:39.275 --> 01:29:42.362
Louis William Wheeler,

01:29:42.404 --> 01:29:46.867
I am so proud of you.
Oh gosh, honey.

01:29:46.908 --> 01:29:50.786
Come on now, come on...

01:29:50.828 --> 01:29:53.914
We both knew it was only
a matter of time.

01:29:56.334 --> 01:30:00.839
Well, I have so much packing
to do, and a realtor and...

01:30:00.881 --> 01:30:03.258
Can I call the kids and tell them?

01:30:03.300 --> 01:30:07.137
Yeah! I'm gonna take a shower./ Okay.

01:31:22.549 --> 01:31:25.301
Well, Rhino...

01:31:25.343 --> 01:31:28.304
We did it.

01:31:39.566 --> 01:31:42.736
I don't know what I thought.

01:31:42.778 --> 01:31:46.031
Maybe if I did a good thing,

01:31:46.073 --> 01:31:49.786
something totally out of character,

01:31:49.828 --> 01:31:53.540
that it would make a difference.

01:31:53.581 --> 01:31:58.795
And it did, I guess,

01:31:58.837 --> 01:32:01.423
to a man I've never seen.

01:32:01.464 --> 01:32:04.343
Probably never talk to again.

01:32:07.012 --> 01:32:09.056
But I did something today

01:32:09.098 --> 01:32:12.726
that you'd be proud of.

01:32:12.768 --> 01:32:16.062
I mean, I think you'd be proud of me.

01:32:19.150 --> 01:32:21.986
Just like I'm proud of you.

01:32:22.027 --> 01:32:26.365
Something I should have
told you every day...

01:32:26.407 --> 01:32:28.367
I'm proud

01:32:28.409 --> 01:32:31.620
of my little man.

01:32:33.540 --> 01:32:37.002
And if you're tired of fighting,

01:32:37.043 --> 01:32:40.881
and... and you need to rest,

01:32:40.922 --> 01:32:44.843
well, then I understand.

01:32:46.761 --> 01:32:49.432
I'll even keep Lauren out of your room.

01:32:52.685 --> 01:32:55.855
Me and your mom...

01:32:55.897 --> 01:32:58.649
we'll be okay...

01:32:58.691 --> 01:33:02.402
We'll be okay.

01:33:22.132 --> 01:33:24.509
Hey, hon.

01:33:24.551 --> 01:33:27.346
How's he doing?

01:33:29.264 --> 01:33:32.017
The same.

01:33:35.479 --> 01:33:37.982
You need to get some rest.

01:33:38.024 --> 01:33:41.110
Let me sit with him for a while.

01:33:41.152 --> 01:33:45.365
My mom's got the kids.
Go home, take a nap.

01:33:45.406 --> 01:33:48.159
Maybe a shower?

01:33:48.201 --> 01:33:51.203
Please?

01:33:54.082 --> 01:33:56.501
I can't.

01:33:56.542 --> 01:33:58.711
I don't wanna be gone if he...

01:33:58.753 --> 01:34:02.465
Dane, if he codes,

01:34:02.507 --> 01:34:06.010
and only if he codes, I'll call you.

01:34:08.097 --> 01:34:11.433
I'm not gonna let him go without you.

01:34:50.932 --> 01:34:54.477
Dane?

01:34:54.519 --> 01:34:56.439
I love you.

01:34:56.480 --> 01:35:00.025
What's not to love?

01:36:36.125 --> 01:36:38.211
You're fired.

01:36:40.129 --> 01:36:42.757
What?

01:36:42.799 --> 01:36:45.886
You can't just fire me.

01:36:45.928 --> 01:36:50.140
My place. I'll fire anybody I want.

01:36:50.182 --> 01:36:54.561
No, I don't mean...
I don't mean you "can't," Ed, I mean...

01:36:54.603 --> 01:36:56.730
Pack up your shit and beat it.

01:37:00.401 --> 01:37:03.780
Fired? Why?

01:37:03.822 --> 01:37:08.492
Because I gave away one guy?
Ed, I've billed out millions...

01:37:08.534 --> 01:37:10.536
Wilson won.
She doesn't need you

01:37:10.577 --> 01:37:12.037
second-guessing her.

01:37:12.079 --> 01:37:13.747
And besides, you're not
the same guy anymore.

01:37:13.747 --> 01:37:17.252
I... I am the same guy, Ed.../
No, you are not!

01:37:17.293 --> 01:37:20.672
I don't want to hear it anymore.

01:37:22.757 --> 01:37:26.553
Over. Done. Get out.

01:37:48.410 --> 01:37:50.871
You know, I used to say
a relationship with you

01:37:50.912 --> 01:37:54.415
was based only on the ability
to make you money.

01:37:56.333 --> 01:37:58.711
It just sounded tough.

01:37:58.752 --> 01:38:01.589
I never really believed it.

01:38:01.630 --> 01:38:05.385
Shut the door, please.

01:38:38.545 --> 01:38:43.299
No, no, no, no, no, no...

01:39:26.136 --> 01:39:27.846
Oh, honey!

01:39:27.888 --> 01:39:32.600
Dad?

01:39:41.986 --> 01:39:45.155
Rhi... Rhino!

01:39:45.197 --> 01:39:48.742
How you doing?/ Fine.

01:39:56.167 --> 01:39:59.045
Hey./ It's gonna be okay.

01:40:00.964 --> 01:40:03.049
It's gonna be okay.

01:40:14.520 --> 01:40:17.440
Come here.

01:40:36.375 --> 01:40:39.420
How's he doing?

01:40:39.462 --> 01:40:42.758
His counts are still coming up.

01:40:42.799 --> 01:40:45.927
He's good.

01:40:45.969 --> 01:40:50.056
Uh, a messenger brought this
to the house. From Blackridge.

01:40:59.942 --> 01:41:02.737
Here's the thing, Elise.

01:41:02.779 --> 01:41:05.948
I didn't take today,

01:41:05.990 --> 01:41:10.368
or yesterday, or the week off.

01:41:10.410 --> 01:41:13.289
I lost my job.

01:41:13.331 --> 01:41:15.374
Ed fired me.

01:41:15.416 --> 01:41:18.419
Oh.

01:41:19.879 --> 01:41:22.590
Thank God!

01:41:46.032 --> 01:41:50.036
What is this?

01:41:55.874 --> 01:41:58.460
Son of a bitch.

01:42:33.540 --> 01:42:37.544
Daddy!/ Jesus, Lauren...!

01:42:37.585 --> 01:42:39.129
Watcha doin'?

01:42:39.170 --> 01:42:41.840
I'm working.
What does it look like I'm doing?

01:42:41.881 --> 01:42:43.924
Doesn't look like you're doing anything.

01:42:43.966 --> 01:42:45.801
I'm making it look easy.

01:42:48.179 --> 01:42:50.765
What?/ Can we sit in your spinny?

01:42:50.807 --> 01:42:53.310
No, you can't sit in my spinny chair.

01:42:53.351 --> 01:42:56.187
Please?

01:42:56.229 --> 01:42:59.190
Okay, come on.

01:43:02.652 --> 01:43:05.281
Getting in?/ I'm too old for that.

01:43:05.322 --> 01:43:09.076
Come on!

01:43:09.118 --> 01:43:13.122
Okay! Scooch over!/ Alright, here we go!

01:43:13.164 --> 01:43:17.501
No!

01:43:17.543 --> 01:43:19.755
Kids, come on, leave your dad alone.

01:43:19.796 --> 01:43:21.423
You gotta get on the bus
in half an hour.

01:43:21.423 --> 01:43:24.843
Come on. Lauren, that hair...

01:43:24.885 --> 01:43:28.096
Do you want the door open or shut?

01:43:28.138 --> 01:43:30.265
Will someone wipe me when I'm done?

01:43:30.307 --> 01:43:31.349
Shut.

01:43:58.795 --> 01:44:01.589
Jensen Group Recruiting, Dane Jensen.

01:44:01.631 --> 01:44:03.132
It's about time you got off your ass...

01:44:03.132 --> 01:44:04.801
and went back to work, isn't it?

01:44:04.842 --> 01:44:06.887
Lou, how you doin'?!

01:44:06.929 --> 01:44:09.598
Oh man, I'm busier than a one-legged man

01:44:09.640 --> 01:44:11.809
in an ass-kicking contest...
and I'm loving it!

01:44:13.477 --> 01:44:16.814
And how about you?
Can't be easy starting over again.

01:44:16.855 --> 01:44:20.191
Oh, I'm... I'm pretty busy.

01:44:20.233 --> 01:44:22.736
Could you be busier?/ Come again?

01:44:22.778 --> 01:44:24.404
Now that I've got
my feet on the ground...

01:44:24.404 --> 01:44:26.782
I've got the go-ahead
to hire some new engineers.

01:44:26.824 --> 01:44:30.619
Engineers?

01:44:30.661 --> 01:44:32.621
Plural?

01:44:32.663 --> 01:44:35.249
Yeah, we're gonna need two
at least to start, maybe three.

01:44:35.290 --> 01:44:38.002
We're flexible on salary.

01:44:38.044 --> 01:44:39.504
And I wouldn't want to talk
to anybody but you, Dane.

01:44:39.504 --> 01:44:41.548
And I never will.

01:44:41.589 --> 01:44:45.301
I appreciate that, Lou. I do.

01:44:45.343 --> 01:44:49.013
And I'm thinking of one name,

01:44:49.055 --> 01:44:52.892
three words, Mohammed Al Farooq.

01:44:52.934 --> 01:44:56.730
Oh, boy./ Hey, Lou...

01:44:56.772 --> 01:44:59.358
You mind if I call you back
in about an hour?

01:44:59.400 --> 01:45:02.069
I've got a daily meeting I can't miss.

01:45:02.111 --> 01:45:03.487
Walnuts?

01:45:03.529 --> 01:45:05.281
Oz says they're his food of choice.

01:45:05.322 --> 01:45:07.616
If you're ever stranded on
a deserted island... walnuts.

01:45:07.616 --> 01:45:11.370
Guess he didn't plan
on being stranded with you.

01:45:17.543 --> 01:45:20.170
You save the receipt for this?

01:45:20.212 --> 01:45:21.630
I think it's here somewhere, why?

01:45:21.672 --> 01:45:23.007
Alright, yeah.

01:45:23.048 --> 01:45:26.011
Tax write-off... business lunch.

01:45:29.139 --> 01:45:32.517
Dane Jensen... husband, father,

01:45:32.559 --> 01:45:34.519
last of the romantics.

